Here I noticed ListingNumber and ListingKey appear more than once in some cases, however in the row there are some new information. So the rows themselves are not duplicates.

Assessment Findings¶

  • Back to Top

    • Tidy¶

    loan_data¶
    • Several columns not needed for analysis; remove unnecessary data
    • Change names of columns with spacing and parenthesis

    Quality¶

    loan_data¶
    • DataFrame has duplicated data in ListingKey and ListingNumber
    • Listing Number is an integer but should be an object
    • Listing Creation Date should be date
    • Term is an integer but should be an object
    • Close date should be a date
    • Listing Category (numeric) is an integer and should be an object
    • Date Credit Pulled is an object should be a date

    Clean Data¶

  • Back to Top

    • Define¶

    • Drop unnecessary data

    For my analysis, there are several columns that I will not need. For example, ListingKey is irrelevant and just takes up memory and resources. I have previewed the data and determined what I will need for exploration of the data set. If I determine later that I removed information that I needed, I can always reload the original csv file into a new dataframe.

    That being said, I will copy the dataframe before dropping columns.

    Exploratory Data Analysis¶

    What is the structure of your dataset?¶

    34 x 113937 List loan data for various loan seekers.

    What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

    The main feature of interest is Occupation and what is the average loan amount by profession.

    Additional features of interest are to identify groups by Income Range, Credit Grade and or Employment Status. I want to see which of these groups are in the majority in this data set. This could be useful information to a banking organization to determine potential clients to target based on the data from this set. We can determine the average Income Range of an applicant and market specific loans that fit their needs and budgets.

    What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

    Occupation listing and Employment Status. Also, details of the loan like Term and Borrower APR.

    Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

    Occupation is a healthy list of 67 titles. Unfortunately, there is a variable for Other, which is understandable, but it is also the largest variable in the set. So, that is vague and may create outliers which cannot be identified. I do not need to create any transformations at this time.

    Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

    One unusual distribution was in Term of loan. I had theorized that more loans would be towards the higher Term of 60, when in fact the maximum count is towards 36. Initially, Term was an integer and I changed it to a category. This is more appropriate in this case since we do not want to perform aggregation to the Term variable. It is a Qualitative variable that I would classify as Ordinal data.

    Yes, I made some changes. I dropped columns I did not want to use for my analysis. I did this to keep my queries organized and not get distracted by data I would not use. If further in the analysis I determined I dropped information that could be useful, I can always reload the original csv file. However, I reviewed the Prosper Loan Data Variable Definitions very carefully to determine what I would require. As a bonus I reduced the original data frame from 68.1 mb to 28.9 mb.

    Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

    First of all, Term was interesting. I would have imagined most loan seekers would go for the higher term of 60 months but, 36 seems to hold the majority across various employment status. Then, I charted EmploymentSatus with CreditGrade, which produced some unusual results in the Employed attribute. It seems those seeking loans that were Employed did not record markings for CreditGrade? That seemed curious. I further investigated the relationship between CreditGrade and IncomeRange.

    Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

    BorrowerRate correlation ot StatedMonthlyIncome showed a few outliers. One where a higher BorrowerRate and a large Monthly income was very clear and noticeable in a Scatter Plot. That prompted me to look at StatedMonthlyIncome to DebtToIncomeRatio. As expected, the higher the monthly income the lower the debt ratio. Although it was a sharp drop in scale. Indicating that a large number of applicants with low monthly income have a high debt ratio.

    Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

    Yes, IncomeRange by BorrowerRate featuring Term; we saw earlier that most loan applicants tend to favor the 36-month term, in this section we see the larger group by IncomeRange have a minimal difference in the category of 36 to 60 Term. 25K to 49.9K range by BorrowerRate were very close by both 36 and 60 Term. Now, when we look at the data in a box plot, we see the two larger groups on the left are close in the medium but are high in 36 Term upper quartile. Our box plot shows a lot of interesting data. We can see no outliers for the 2 largest groups from left to right. In the Not displayed category we see several outliers. Unfortunately, we do not have a definition for Not displayed, I assume they did not give that information, or it was private information. I thought it would be interesting to see a box plot of IncomeRange to LoanOriginalAmount. In the final plot we see outliers in every category. The medium is significantly erratic for each category concerning Term.

    Conclusion¶

  • Back to Top

    • To conclude, the data set featured loan applicant data. I explored several variables and compared the more interesting variables by Income Range of the applicants. I performed some bivariate exploration to discover trends in Employment Status by Term of loans. As well as, in category of Credit Grade. Then, I explored Credit Grade by Income Range. My inquiries revealed trends for the 25k to 49.9k to be the larger group on loan applicants in this data set. I ended my analysis with box plots on Income Range and Borrower APR and Loan Amount.

    Originally, I sought to identify the average loan amount by occupation. As I dive deeper in my analysis, I sought to narrow the categories down to by employment status and income range.

    Listing by income range would be a more general category and it is a major factor for loan applicants. This could be used as a baseline for what loan amount an applicant may qualify for.
